subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis
. Body length, female, 
26.69 mm
(24.67–30.18; n=5); male 
32.02 mm
(31.71–32.32; n=2). Female: Head with two arc-shaped elevations joined anteriorly to middle ocellus (
Figs. 23 and 24
), which lies between these structures and above upper margin of eyes; area between parapsidal line and mesoscutal disc with sparse punctures (separated by three or more times their diameter); wings dark brown with blue-purple iridescence (
Fig. 26
); pubescence evenly black; integument of terga evenly black; T1 to T3 with very dense, minute punctures on discal and sublateral areas; T2 to T4 with very minute hairs, T5 hair 0.99–1.18 (length respect MOD). Male: T1 to T5 yellowish with black bands on posterior margin, T6 mainly yellowish with a posterior band lighter than on previous terga, T7 and lateral areas of T2 to T7 yellowish; T6 and T7 with long, dense, yellowish hairs, dark-brown apically (
Fig. 30
); posterior tibia internal distal extreme with a robust projection as long as wide, anterior margin with noticeable lobe (
Fig. 32
); length of hairs on terga respect MOD, T2 0.20–0.69, T3 0.31–0.39, T4 with minute hairs, T5 0.26–0.50; tip of lateral process of the gonostylus ending broad, oval (
Fig. 109
).

Distribution ( Fig. 134 ). Present in Costa Rica , Guatemala , Honduras , and Mexico , in the following ecoregions (
Dinerstein et al . 2017
): Humid forests of the Central American Atlantic, Pine-oak forests of Central America, Mountainous forests of Chiapas , Seasonal humid forests of Costa Rica , Isthmus-Atlantic humid forests, Scrubland of the Central Mexican Plateau, Mesoamerican mangroves of the Gulf of Mexico and the Caribbean, Mountainous forests of Oaxaca , Humid forests of Petén-Veracruz, Sierra de los Tuxtlas, Humid forests of the Sierra Madre of Chiapas , Pine-oak forests of the Sierra Madre of Oaxaca , Pine-oak forests of the Sierra Madre del Sur, Pine-oak forests of the Sierra Madre Oriental, Mountainous forests of Talamanca, Humid forests of Veracruz , Mountainous forests of Veracruz , Dry forests of the Yucatan Peninsula, and Humid forests of the Yucatan Peninsula. Broad altitudinal distribution from 0 to 1992 m .

- Genal area with sparse punctation (
Fig. 33
); pubescence and integument black; wings dark-brown with strong blue-green iridescence distal extreme papillate with greenish blue iridescence (
Fig. 36
); vertex with punctures slightly smaller than those on clypeus (Central and Southern 
Mexico
)........................................................ 

X. mexicanorum
